  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum of 30 years if the laundering involves proceeds from certain specified unlawful activities\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential civil monetary penalties\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential criminal charges for related offenses\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Damage to personal and professional reputation\n\nThe specific penalties can vary based on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Nature of the underlying criminal activity\n- Individual's criminal history\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n\nThese penalties are typically enforced under statutes like the Money Laundering Control Act and the Bank Secrecy Act. Prosecution is generally handled by federal agencies such as the Department of Justice.",
